					<div class="modal-body">
						<div class="modal-content">
							<p>
								Cataract is a cloudy natural lens of the eye. The lens become cloudy instead of being crystal clear.
								Cataracts block light, making it difficult to see clearly. Cataracts are very common as you get older often
								develop slowly and can affect one or both eyes.
								How will the cataract affect you?
								When the cataracts develop, initially you will not feel any difference but over time, cataracts can make
								your vision blurry, hazy, or less colourful. You may have trouble reading or doing other everyday
								activities. Drivers will get glare as the cataracts grow.
							</p>

							<h5>Examples of cataract</h5>
							<img src="/images/disease/cataract.jpg" id="cataract-image" alt="exemples of cataract">
							<hr>
							<h5>Causes of cataracts</h5>
							<p>
								Cataracts mainly occur as a you grow up. There are many other diseases that than cause the cataract to grow
								faster or at a younger age for example Diabetes and inflammation of the middle and internal layers of the
								eye, very rarely people are born with cataract.
							</p>
							<hr>
							<h5>Other risk factors for developing cataract</h5>
							<ul>
								<li>Smoking</li>
								<li>Drinking too much alcohol</li>
								<li>Have a family history of cataracts</li>
								<li>Have had an eye injury, eye surgery, or radiation treatment on your upper body</li>
								<li>Have spent a lot of time in the sun</li>
								<li>ake steroids (medicines used to treat a variety of health problems, like arthritis and rashes)</li>
							</ul>
							<hr>
							<h5>Treatment</h5>
							<p>
								During the past decade cataract treatment evolved significantly from a very large incision to the use of
								Femtolaser. That is performed under a topical anaesthesia with a very quick recovery time.
								The human lens is then replaced with artificial lens. Cataract surgery can correct both near and distance
								vision. They minimize or eliminate the need for reading glasses after surgery. Conventional "monofocal"
								lenses only correct for distance vision, meaning reading glasses
								are still needed after surgery. Multifocal IOLs (Intraocular Lens) can be an option in some patients to help
								improve both distance and near vision. "Toric" implants are available to correct astigmatism.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
					<a href="#" class="modal-close modal-close-bottom">Close</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="eye-disease-glaucoma">
